            "creation_date": 1596906580,
            "body": "<p>Whenever there is a doubt always use mathematics as the mathematical proofs are more palatable like strong intuitions.<\/p>\n<p>Let <code>n<\/code> = size of input.<\/p>\n<p>The innermost loop or lets call it as the 3rd loop runs for <code>j+1<\/code> number of times.<\/p>\n<p>The inner loop or 2nd loop runs for <code>i*i - i<\/code> number of times.<\/p>\n<p>Finally, the outer loop for <code>n<\/code> times.<\/p>\n<p>So, the number of iterations for the entire program can be expressed in mathematical terms as shown in the following figure:<\/p>\n<p><a href=\"https://i.sstatic.net/LR1RO.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/LR1RO.jpg\" alt=\"enter image description here\" /><\/a><\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 63318145,
            "question_id": 63315829
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/6yBJv.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 19158880,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 13995128,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/13995128/kuzmink13",
                "reputation": 336,
                "display_name": "KuzminK13"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 4.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1596893981,
            "creation_date": 1596893981,
            "body": "<p>When you have multiple levels of for loops, analyze the complexity of each loop in isolation and then multiply them together.<\/p>\n<p>In this example, the complexity of the first loop is <code>O(n)<\/code>, like you said.<\/p>\n<p>The complexity of the second loop is <code>O(n^2)<\/code> because in the worst case, the number of operations you have to perform is on the order of <code>i*i<\/code> which could be as big as <code>n^2<\/code>. It doesn't matter that it doesn't start at zero either because in an expression like <code>O(n^2 - n)<\/code>, everything but the highest order term gets ignored.<\/p>\n<p>The third loop also takes <code>O(n^2)<\/code> because in the worst case, you could have as many as <code>j<\/code> operations would again could be as big as <code>n^2<\/code>.<\/p>\n<p>Lastly <code>a++<\/code> happens in constant time. Multiply everything together and you have a complexity of <code>O(n^5)<\/code>.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 63316036,
            "question_id": 63315829
        }
